        // Put the custom class object into the Bundle
        bundle.putParcelable("myData", myData);

        // Set the Bundle as arguments for the fragment
        fragmentB.setArguments(bundle);

        // Replace or add the fragment to your activity
        getParentFragmentManager().beginTransaction()
                .replace(R.id.fragment_container, fragmentB)
                .addToBackStack(null)
                .commit();
    }

    // ...
}
```

3. In the receiving fragment (`FragmentB`), retrieve the custom class object from the `Bundle` using `getArguments()`:

```java
public class FragmentB extends Fragment {
    private static final String ARG_MY_DATA = "myData";

    private MyData myData;

    @Override
    public void onCreate(@Nullable Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);

        // Get the Bundle from the arguments
        Bundle bundle = getArguments();

        // Check if the Bundle is not null
        if (bundle != null) {
            // Extract the custom class object from the Bundle
            myData = bundle.getParcelable(ARG_MY_DATA);

            // Use the custom class object
            if (myData != null) {
                Log.d("FragmentB", "Name: " + myData.getName());
                Log.d("FragmentB", "Age: " + myData.getAge());
            }
        }
    }

    // ...
}
```

In this example, `FragmentA` creates an instance of the `MyData` class and puts it into a `Bundle` using `putParcelable()`. Then, it sets the `Bundle` as arguments for `FragmentB`.

In `FragmentB`, the `MyData` object is retrieved from the `Bundle` using `getParcelable()` in the `onCreate()` method.

Note that if your custom class implements the `Serializable` interface instead of `Parcelable`, you would use `putSerializable()` and `getSerializable()` methods instead of `putParcelable()` and `getParcelable()`, respectively.

