To receive the argument values passed through a `Bundle` in a fragment, you can use the `getArguments()` method in the fragment's lifecycle methods, such as `onCreate()` or `onCreateView()`. Here's an example of how to do it:

Suppose you have a custom class `MyData` that implements `Parcelable` or `Serializable`, and you're passing an instance of this class as an argument to a fragment using a `Bundle`.

In the fragment where you want to receive the argument values:

```java
public class MyFragment extends Fragment {
    private static final String ARG_MY_DATA = "myData";

    private MyData myData;

    public static MyFragment newInstance(MyData data) {
        MyFragment fragment = new MyFragment();
        Bundle args = new Bundle();
        args.putParcelable(ARG_MY_DATA, data);
        fragment.setArguments(args);
        return fragment;
    }

    @Override
    public void onCreate(@Nullable Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);

        // Get the Bundle from the arguments
        Bundle bundle = getArguments();

        // Check if the Bundle is not null
        if (bundle != null) {
            // Extract the custom class object from the Bundle
            myData = bundle.getParcelable(ARG_MY_DATA);
        }
    }

    @Nullable
    @Override
    public View onCreateView(@NonNull LayoutInflater inflater, @Nullable ViewGroup container, @Nullable Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        View view = inflater.inflate(R.layout.fragment_my, container, false);

        // Use the myData object here
        if (myData != null) {
            // Access the properties of myData
            String name = myData.getName();
            int age = myData.getAge();

            // Update the UI or perform other operations with the data
            TextView nameTextView = view.findViewById(R.id.nameTextView);
            nameTextView.setText(name);

            TextView ageTextView = view.findViewById(R.id.ageTextView);
            ageTextView.setText(String.valueOf(age));
        }

        return view;
    }
}
```

In this example:

1. The `newInstance()` method is used to create a new instance of `MyFragment` and pass the `MyData` object as an argument using a `Bundle`.
2. In the `onCreate()` method, the `Bundle` is retrieved using `getArguments()`, and the `MyData` object is extracted from the `Bundle` using `getParcelable()` (or `getSerializable()` if your class implements `Serializable`).
3. In the `onCreateView()` method, you can access the properties of the `MyData` object and use them to update the UI or perform other operations.

Note that you can also retrieve the argument values in other lifecycle methods, such as `onViewCreated()` or `onActivityCreated()`, depending on your use case and when you need to access the data.

By following this approach, you can effectively receive and use the argument values passed through a `Bundle` in your fragment.

To insert the values from a `Bundle` into a class object, you can create a constructor or setter methods in your class that accept the values from the `Bundle`. Here's an example:

Suppose you have a custom class `MyData` that you want to populate with values from a `Bundle`:

```java
public class MyData {
    private String name;
    private int age;

    // Constructor
    public MyData(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }

    // Getters and setters
    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }

    public void setName(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public int getAge() {
        return age;
    }

    public void setAge(int age) {
        this.age = age;
    }
}
```

In your fragment, you can retrieve the values from the `Bundle` and create an instance of `MyData` using the constructor or setter methods:

```java
public class MyFragment extends Fragment {
